TCL Procedures:
    TCL (Tool Command Language), a procedure is a reusable code block that can be called multiple times with different inputs.
    It is similar to a function or subroutine in other programming languages.
    It is used to avoid same code being repeated in multiple locations.
syntax:
      proc procedureName {arguments} {
       body of the proc
      }
      procedureName
Example 1:
      proc Physical_design {} {
       puts "Floorplan, Powerplan!"
      }
      Physical_design
i) Proedure with multiple arguments:
      proc add {a b} {
       return [expr $a+$b]
      }
      puts [add 10 30]
      
ii) Procedure with variable arguments:
      proc avg {numbers} {
       set sum 0
       foreach number $numbers {
       set sum [expr $sum + $number]
      }
       set average [expr $sum/[llength $numbers]]
       return $average
      }
      puts [avg {70 80 50 60}]
      puts [avg {70 80 50 }]
      
iii) Procedure with Default arguments:
        Default arguments are used to provide default values that can be used if no value is provided.
        
      proc add {a {b 100} } {
       return [expr $a+$b]
      }
      puts [add 10 30]
      puts [add 10]
      
iv) Procedure with return keyword:
      proc add {x1 x2} {
      set c [expr $x1 + $x2]
      return $c
      }
      puts "Addition of x1 and x2 is:[add 5 10]"

v) Recursive Procedure:
      proc factorial {number} {
       if {$number <= 1} {
       return 1
       }
       return [expr $number * [factorial [expr $number - 1]]]
      }
      puts [factorial 3]
      puts [factorial 5]
